 able to combine the early twentieth century dramatic discourse with that of the late Soviet era. Having built a bridge between the two eras, Sadur prepared the rise of the new Russian drama of the 2000s.  afunded by National Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Program  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aRussian drama. 7aLITERARY COLLECTIONS / Russian & Former Soviet Union.2bisacsh1 aLipovetsky, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeterson, Nadya L., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSarsenov, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aNational Endowment for the Humanities and The Andrew W. Mellon Foundation Humanities Open Book Programefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015z978311068814608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z978311102370040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781618117083?locatt=mode:legacyzOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781618117083zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781618117083/original  a978-3-11-068814-6 Academic Studies Press Backlist eBook-Package 2008-2015c2008d2015  a978-3-11-102370-0 Academic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2014b2014  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA